lining markup?"),n.li("**Imports** \u2014 note which imports are used. If your edits remove the last usage of an import, delete that import line."),t.h2("Rules (must follow)"),t.paragraph("\u26A0\uFE0F **NEVER use inline `style={}`.** This is the single most common mistake and edits that introduce inline styles will be rejected. Always express styles as Tailwind utility classes (e.g. `bg-[#F7F7F7]`, `top-[600px]`, `w-[201px]`, `text-[#333]`) or by updating/composing existing CSS variables. Adding `style={{ backgroundColor: '...' }}` or `style={{ top: '...' }}` is **always wrong**, even if the element has no classes yet.");let a=t.ol();a.li("**No inline styles \u2014 use Tailwind classes or CSS variables.** For any new style, either add a Tailwind utility class (including arbitrary-value syntax like `bg-[#hex]`) or update the relevant CSS variable. Never add a `style={}` prop."),a.li("**Use existing abstractions.** Before hardcoding a color, spacing, or layout value, search for a CSS variable, Tailwind theme token, or design token that matches. Use the abstraction. Only hardcode a raw value if no match exists."),a.li("**Reuse existing components.** If a component or wrapper already encapsulates the element you need to change, modify that component\u2014do not bypass it by inlining its markup into a parent."),a.li("**Clean up dead code.** After every edit, check: are there now-unused imports, variables, or functions? Remove them."),a.li("**No raw sub-pixel values.** Values like `w-[85.5px]` or `left: 362px` are design-canvas measurements. Round to the nearest whole number or Tailwind spacing step. Prefer flex/grid/margin/padding over absolute positioning unless the element was already absolutely positioned."),a.li("**Choose the right positioning mode.** The design tool exports `position: absolute` for everything, but that is often wrong in code. Before applying positioning, reason about the element's role: use `fixed` for elements that stay on screen during scroll (e.g. sticky headers, floating action buttons, modals/overlays), use `absolute` only for elements positioned relative to a specific parent container (e.g. badges, tooltips, decorative overlays within a card), and prefer normal document flow (`static`) with flex/grid layout whenever possible."),a.li("Never use `!important` in CSS."),t.h2("Scope"),t.paragraph(e.totalChanges>1?`Apply the ${e.totalChanges} design changes below.`:"Apply the design change below."),t.paragraph("Only change visual treatment (styles, layout, content) unless explicitly stated. Do not alter application logic, state, or data flow. If an edited element represents a particular UI state (e.g. the active item in a list), decide whether the change applies to that instance only or to every element in that state, and apply accordingly."),e.hasModifiedText&&t.paragraph("**Dynamic content.** Text changes showing dates, times, counts, or user-specific data (e.g. `April 10 \u2192 April 9`, `5:39 \u2192 12:50`) are snapshot values captured at a point in time. If the code renders this text dynamically, leave it unchanged\u2014do not hardcode the snapshot value."),e.hasMovedNode&&t.paragraph('**Positions.** All indices are 0-based and refer to the original markup order before any edits. When applying multiple moves, plan all edits against the original tree first\u2014each move uses original indices regardless of other edits. Example: given [A,B,C,D], "move index 3\u21920" then "move index 1\u21922" means move D then B; B is still at index 1 in the original tree.'),(r.includes("screenshot")||r.includes("partialScreenshot"))&&t.paragraph("**Reference images** (before/after screenshots) are attached. Study the **before** image to locate each element mentioned in the changes. Study the **after** image to understand the intended visual result. After editing, mentally compare your changes against the after image to verify correctness. Do **not** use reference images for code imports or `figma:asset` URLs, and do **not** invent changes beyond what the diff describes."),e.hasAddedNode&&t.paragraph("**Added elements.** For new elements, use the **Reference** JSON as a guide for structure and props. Use existing components and patterns from the codebase where possible. **Asset images** may be attached\u2014one per image ref, keyed by the hash in **Image ref(s)**. For each image, **import** it (e.g. `import myImage from 'figma:asset/<hash>.png'`) and use the **imported variable** in `src={myImage}`. Do **not** put the `figma:asset/...` URL directly in `src=\"...\"`."),(e.hasAddedNode||e.hasRemovedNode)&&t.paragraph("**Preserve rendering patterns.** If elements in the target area are rendered from data (e.g. `.map()` over an array, loops), modify the data source or rendering logic rather than replacing it with hardcoded elements. When the diff shows multiple individual elements added or removed at the same source location, the intent is usually to change the underlying data or filter\u2014not to rewrite the rendering into static markup.")}(S,T,t),function(e,t,r,n){for(let N of d){let d=r.get(N);if(d?.length)for(let r of(t.h2(c[N]),d)){var s,o,u,p,E,C,j,S;let d=r[0];if(d)if(1===r.length)switch(N){case i.Y7.Color:s=e,o=t,u=d,p=n,u.targetKind!==i.$6.Prop?console.warn("Color change target kind is not prop",u):(o.h3(m(s,(0,l.rc)(u),u,p)),v(o,u));break;case i.Y7.Content:h(e,t,d,n);break;case i.Y7.Layout:g(e,t,d,n);break;case i.Y7.Typography:E=e,C=t,j=d,S=n,j.targetKind!==i.$6.Prop?console.warn("Typography change target kind is not prop",j):(C.h3(m(E,(0,l.b8)(j.propName),j,S)),v(C,j));break;default:!function(e,t,r,n){let a,l=b(r),s=k(r),o=w(r),u=e.changePrefix();if(r.op===i.vZ.Removed){let e=o??s;u+=`${l} removed${e?` (was \`${e}\`)`:""}`}else r.op===i.vZ.Modified&&void 0!==o&&void 0!==s?u+=`${l}: \`${o}\` \u{2192} \`${s}\``:r.op===i.vZ.Added&&void 0!==s?u+=`${l} set to \`${s}\``:r.op===i.vZ.Moved&&void 0!==r.oldPosition&&void 0!==r.newPosition?(u+=`${l} moved (position \`${r.oldPosition}\`